    {
        "content": "<p>That paper seems to say what the category of models is like (i.e. that the models of a Horn theory must be what is sometimes called an \"algebraic category\"), but not what the \"classifying model\" is like</p>",
        "id": 433431604,
        "sender_full_name": "Evan Washington",
        "timestamp": 1713237047
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What you want is probably Theorem 25 and 27 in Section 3.3 of Wechler's <em>Universal Algebra for Computer Scientists</em>. They give the following corollary (this section has three variants of what kind of implications they allow, infinitely many variables, finitely many variables, and finitely many premises, Horn clauses being those with finitely many premises):<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/3IMAbWC1OArrqxeUy4S4-fPX/e8c0583f-3493-42ba-af02-9cc8a1b6d080.jpg\">e8c0583f-3493-42ba-af02-9cc8a1b6d080.jpg</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/3IMAbWC1OArrqxeUy4S4-fPX/e8c0583f-3493-42ba-af02-9cc8a1b6d080.jpg\" title=\"e8c0583f-3493-42ba-af02-9cc8a1b6d080.jpg\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/3IMAbWC1OArrqxeUy4S4-fPX/e8c0583f-3493-42ba-af02-9cc8a1b6d080.jpg\"></a></div>",
